  <annotation nid="1140">
    <title>de el ser de Díos</title>
    <content><p><strong>Folio 1 recto, column A, line 1<br />
Escolio 4 recto, lines 1–2</strong></p>

<p>Ximénez places his heading for the first chapter of the <em>Escolios</em> (“Cap. 1. de el ser de Díos”) in the margin of the first page of the <em>Popol Vuh</em>, which introduces the principal deities involved in the K'iche' account of creation. In the <em>Escolios </em>, Ximénez examines the nature of these creator gods and the nature of divinity in the <em>Popol Vuh</em>, which he refers to as “duodernidad” (deities are placed in pairs, rather than a monotheistic trinity). He further debates the "proper" use of these deities’ names in catechizing, and ultimately supports their utter extirpation. He argued that although Tz’aqol Bitol was a linguistically accurate name for God (Framer, Shaper), it could easily be a demonic distraction from the true faith. Instead, he recommends the continued use of “Dios.”</p></content>
